Indian Equities: Mobile-Phone Operators, Akzo, Patni, Reliance

-- B y   H e m a l   S a v a i   a n d   S h i k h a r   B a l w a n i
-- 
2011-07-25T11:28:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-25/indian-equities-mobile-phone-operators-akzo-patni-reliance.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Indian trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the 3:30 p.m. close local time.  India’s Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or Sensex,
rose 0.8 percent to 18,871.29. The BSE200 Index advanced 0.8
percent to 2,339.30.  Mobile-phone operators:  Reliance Communications Ltd. (RCOM)  , the country’s second-largest mobile-phone operator, paced
gains among peers after larger rival  Bharti Airtel Ltd. (BHARTI)   on July 22 raised wireless call rates for the first time in
more than two years. Reliance surged 15 percent to 107.75
rupees, the most since May 2009. Bharti jumped 5.2 percent to
432.65 rupees, the highest close since Oct. 1, 2009, while  Idea
Cellular Ltd. (IDEA)   rallied 8.3 percent to 92.45 rupees, the
highest since July 2, 2008.  Akzo Nobel India Ltd. (AKZO)   increased 4.4 percent to
978.80 rupees to a record after Managing Director Amit Jain said
in Kolkata that the chemical company will invest 500 million
rupees in a plant in the southern city of Hyderabad to raise
paint-making capacity to 110 million liters from 80 million
liters.  Pantaloon Retail Ltd. (PF IN),  India ’s largest publicly
traded retailer by value, climbed 1.5 percent to 338.25 rupees,
the highest since Jan. 12. Overseas companies could be allowed
to own as much as 51 percent of stores that sell more than one
brand if they invest a minimum of $100 million, a panel of
bureaucrats in  New Delhi  recommended on July 22, according to a
finance ministry official.  Patni Computer Systems Ltd. (PATNI)  , a  software company ,
sank 3.4 percent to 321.65 rupees, the lowest close since May
19. It posted a group loss of 515.2 million rupees in the second
quarter ended June, compared with a profit of 1.47 billion
rupees a year earlier, according to an exchange filing today.  Reliance Industries Ltd. (RIL)  , the nation’s largest
company by market value, rose 1.1 percent to 882.85 rupees, the
highest close since June 30. India’s cabinet approved July 22 a
deal for BP Plc to buy stakes in Reliance’s oil and natural gas
blocks.  To contact the reporter on this story:
